The paper deals with a communication model involving multiple access channels, state-dependent channels, and knowledge of states at encoders. These topics are typically studied in the information theory (cs.IT) and machine learning (cs.MM) communities. The paper also discusses the use of Gel'fand-Pinsker binning, which is a technique commonly used in source coding (cs.SI) and network information theory (cs.NI). Finally, the paper considers the Gaussian case, which is relevant to the field of signal processing (cs.LG).
